The aim of the method is to more accurately assess applicants in the evaluation of asylum applications. The measure was taken after the Swedish Migrationverket Agency was criticised for failures in determining the correct age of some refugees who lied about their age.
To date, the Swedish Migration Agency has submitted 6880 cases to investigate, and the Forensic Medical Agency has now published a total of 2481 tests conducted from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
80 percent (2002) were considered to be over 18 years of age, while in another 25 cases, the Forensic Medical Agency considered that the surveyed was “probable over the age of 18.”
In an additional 423 cases, it was decided that the question was “probable under the age of 18.”
The tests shall only be taken if the age of the disputed person is disputed.
According to Johan Gørsson of the Forensic Medical Agency, the results correspond to the previous month.
“In comparison to last month’s statistics are held in busy tracks and numbers are very similar,” he told The Local.
A higher number of applicants whose age has been estimated to be over the age of 18 does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers lie about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and stated that in 442 cases it was found that “the person concerned is 18 years old or older.”
The Svenska Dagbladet newspaper investigated 581 published cases and found that in 243 cases, the person said he would be 18 this year.
Criticism also awaited the medical method of determining age, which includes the X-ray of wisdom teeth and MRI scans of knee joints, which are then assessed by dentists and X-rayologists.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, who deals, among other things, with the assessment of the biological maturity of people to determine the age when he passed through puberty.
“I had reason to think about this issue, and I don’t think these types of measurements to assess age are correct.
The assessment of biological age is in some sense very uncertain.
If we can’t determine age with accuracy, we shouldn’t pretend the opposite,” Metro said.
Forensic medical agency Agency’s Gêøransson advocated the decision by saying: “In general, it can be said that the risk of misjudgment of a child as an adult is small.
The highest risk is the fact that the person being asked is just below the age of 18, which in this case corresponds to 10 per cent of all respondents.
