NHS prescribes controversial HIV treatment for 10,000 patients
Since September, patients will have access to ‘transformative’ HIV prevention treatments based on the Supreme Court’s decision on funding for NHS.
The English National Health Service (NSH) reported that the Pre-Exposure Profylaxis (PREP) pill, which is taken before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through a health service to approximately 10,000 patients within a three-year trial period.
NSH agreed to finance the trial period after the Court of Appeal supported the decision of the Supreme Court last year with the statement that NHS had funds to pay for PrEP despite the statement that the drug should be financed by local authorities.
The decision, announced Thursday, adopted the NHS England from the mouth of CEO Simon Stevens as a “significant intervention” while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a “decisive moment”.
The sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to begin receiving patients. Other clinics will join in October and by April 2018 there will be a full implementation across England.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PREP) is an HIV drug given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of transmission of HIV among at-risk patients.
Pre-sex application means that there is enough specific drugs in the patient’s body to prevent infection.
These drugs can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Tested patients include gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and people with HIV positive partners who are not successfully treated.
Clinics will identify eligible participants who sign consent to participate in testing, including men, women, transgender people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with GP in the UK can also apply in their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The program will come to taxpayers for £10 million and NHS England signed a drug distribution contract this week after obtaining an international public contract.
The trial period is designed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: “This important intervention should complement and fully benefit from the ever-increasing and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It’s another milestone in more than thirty years of trying to stop one of the biggest challenges to human health.”
Deborah Gold, Executive Director of NAT (National Aids Trust), said: “We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is administered correctly and at risk to patients, it will offer the possibility of transforming the English HIV epidemic.
Since September, NSH has been offering patients at high risk of HIV infection a new powerful tool that is individually controlled and is not subject to the need to talk to a partner, which will improve the quality of many lives.
We accept this statement with pleasure.”
Ian Green, Chief Executive Officer of Terrence Higgins Trust, said: “The number one limit must be a rapid deployment of tests across the country; we must ensure its availability to every patient.
“We now have a PrEP test drug and we are on track to protect more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV infection.”
Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: “The beginning of the PrEP trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delay and delay by the government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Following tests will bring us one step closer to a full understanding of the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that we start the tests as soon as possible across the country to protect those exposed to HIV and to end the spread of HIV in society.”
